{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17656014","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17656014"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:10:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:10:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18711"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18711","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18711"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.45,0.1,0,0.25,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11443"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77038"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11443","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11443"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18711"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62544"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10643"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26499"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26506"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77038","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77038"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring lactation, milk production is regulated by multiple feedback mechanisms to match infant feeding demands.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary feedback mechanism controlling prolactin secretion during lactation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hypothalamic dopamine inhibition","Oestrogen suppression","Milk protein concentration","Direct feedback by prolactin","Oxytocin negative feedback"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypothalamic dopamine inhibition\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary feedback mechanism controlling prolactin secretion. Dopamine, acting as prolactin inhibiting factor, is continuously released from the hypothalamus to suppress prolactin secretion. When an infant suckles, this inhibition is reduced, allowing prolactin levels to rise and stimulate milk production.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOestrogen suppression\u003C/strong\u003E - While oestrogen can influence lactation, it is not the primary feedback mechanism for prolactin control\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMilk protein concentration\u003C/strong\u003E - Local factors in the breast can affect milk production but do not directly control prolactin secretion\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect feedback by prolactin\u003C/strong\u003E - While prolactin levels do influence the hypothalamus, this occurs through intermediary pathways rather than direct feedback\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOxytocin negative feedback\u003C/strong\u003E - Oxytocin is responsible for milk ejection but does not directly regulate prolactin secretion\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis tonic inhibition by dopamine allows for rapid increases in prolactin secretion when needed, as removal of inhibition is faster than stimulation of production.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Prolactin secretion is tonically inhibited by dopamine released from the hypothalamus, known as prolactin inhibiting factor.","Suckling reduces dopamine release, allowing prolactin levels to rise and stimulate milk production.","When milk accumulates in the breast, local factors inhibit further milk production through feedback inhibition."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Hall J. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2021."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62544"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18711"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62544","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62544"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T22:49:07+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T22:49:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11443"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77038"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4935","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4935"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd5a","name":"Reproductive System (Fe